<TITLE>First Cancer Day draws hundreds</TITLE>
<TEXT>
Delaney Clements mom Wendy Reese drys a tear before addressing the first Western Colorado Cancer Day in the Colorado Mesa Unveristy Meyer Ballroom Saturday afternoon Daughter Emma Jo Campbell looks up to mom By Katie Langford Saturday January 28 2017 For all of the pain and struggle that are often associated with cancer it was the common link for a vibrant community that gathered at Colorado Mesa University on Saturday for the first Western Colorado Cancer Day Nearly 300 people came to the event organized by the St Mary s Survivorship Program which Coordinator Debra Hesse said was sparked by a patient survey last year Every speaker is based on what our patients are dealing with she said Hesse was planning for 200 people to attend and 294 people registered for the day That confirms people are wanting resources she said To be in a room with 300 people who get it is pretty powerful Keynote speaker Wendy Reece spoke of her role as a caregiver for her daughter Delaney Clements who died in March after living with cancer for five years Delaney always told me that living life to the fullest with cancer is a type of therapy and I fully believe that she said When you think you re doing it wrong you re not In caregiving there is only love and that s never wrong Reece said she learned many lessons about how to be a good caregiver and most of them centered on learning how to care for herself too Being healthy and taking care of yourself does not take away from your ability to care for your loved one she said Grand Junction resident Jody Turano who was diagnosed with blood cancer four years ago said she came to learn more about the resources that are available Everything is in one place so you don t have to make a million phone calls finding those resources They ve done a wonderful job with it she said It s always good to be around other people dealing with similar situations and to be able to network 
